illoughby present possible course topics, themes, concepts, and approaches while offering practical advice on materials and strategies helpful for teaching courses from a global perspective in today's teaching environment for today's students. In their discussions of pedagogy, syllabus organization, fostering students' historical empathy, and connecting students with their community, Wiesner-Hanks and Willoughby draw readers into the process of strategically designing courses that will enable students to analyze gender and sexuality in history, whether their students are new to this process or hold powerful and personal commitments to the issues it raises.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aHistoryxStudy and teaching (Higher) 0aHistoryxStudy and teaching (Higher). 0aHistoryxStudy and teaching (Secondary) 0aHistoryxStudy and teaching (Secondary). 0aSexxHistoryxStudy and teaching (Higher) 0aSexxHistoryxStudy and teaching (Higher). 0aSexxHistoryxStudy and teaching (Secondary) 0aSexxHistoryxStudy and teaching (Secondary). 0aWomen's studies. 7aHISTORY / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh1 aWilloughby, Urmi Engineer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478002475zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478002475423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478002475.jpg  a978-3-11-069633-2  DUK eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles